ho want an 8% interest payment every six months. Which is the lower rate?","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]},{"object":"block","type":"list-item","data":{"direction":"auto"},"ref":"ce060b32-208f-43ea-a2ad-60942b466fd5","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"8793bd0a-c67c-40c5-8b79-c97cd460a6e4","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"An online bank is offering to pay 0.25% interest per month on deposits. Your local bank offers to pay 0.75% interest quarterly (every 3 months). Which is the higher interest rate?","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]},{"object":"block","type":"list-item","data":{"direction":"auto"},"ref":"12024cb0-e1a7-4391-9559-3afabce838d7","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"dc074a72-af8b-472f-8feb-6b36d40b6f92","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Which do you prefer: a bank account that pays 5% per year (EAR) for three years or","marks":[]}],"data":{}},{"object":"block","type":"ordered-list","data":{"listOptionType":"a","startValue":1},"ref":"96e01a6d-2f64-4edf-b540-2acd49aebab1","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"list-item","data":{"direction":"auto"},"ref":"8e211d2a-7d92-4422-9a07-a2200911e96f","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"8bf6380a-fcb4-41b4-bac5-5b703e509436","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"an account that pays 2.5% every six months for three years?","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]},{"object":"block","type":"list-item","data":{"direction":"auto"},"ref":"4d759238-369b-461d-a373-4e893aaba889","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"c42dca24-454a-4f3d-afcd-f93e252c852f","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"an account that pays 7.5% every 18 months for three years?","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]},{"object":"block","type":"list-item","data":{"direction":"auto"},"ref":"f69d8fed-f5af-4d7f-a1ee-a2ae945dda97","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"b6a05a83-0eba-4a5e-96fe-8bcc75e40c04","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"an account that pays 0.5% per month for three years?","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}]}]},{"object":"block","type":"list-item","data":{"direction":"auto"},"ref":"cf62effb-ba09-45e4-b343-2e58d094a5da","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"9c580d41-c91c-4b4e-8b93-479d21cd0e95","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"You have been offered a job with an unusual bonus structure. As long as you stay with the firm, you will get an extra $70,000 every seven years, starting seven years from now. What is the present value of this incentive if you plan to work for the company for 42 years and the interest rate is 6% (EAR)?","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}]}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""},"ref":"b02a51f0-91e6-4256-b760-a0ec6224d3b7"}]}]},{"columns":[{"stageElements":[{"type":"stage-element-image","config":{"url":"urn:aero:4ab45a10-44e0-11ed-bcef-d5307f42495c","alt":"","caption":"","layout":{"captionPosition":"Below"},"credit":"","activityLabel":"","activityTitle":""},"height":37,"ref":"429bfd05-c87c-4936-9a66-8b6d35a42294"}]}]},{"columns":[{"stageElements":[{"type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"ordered-list","data":{"listOptionType":"1","startValue":8},"ref":"f46da968-eb5f-462c-ad5e-36729d006bd9","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"list-item","data":{"direction":"auto"},"ref":"e40ec497-cdbb-48e7-9981-81deddb59bf5","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"35a8b6cd-7288-4a31-8675-06b64a6780a0","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"You have found three investment choices for a one-year deposit: 10% APR compounded monthly, 10% APR compounded annually, and 9% APR compounded daily. Compute the EAR for each investment choice. (Assume that there are 365 days in the year.)","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]},{"object":"block","type":"list-item","data":{"direction":"auto"},"ref":"25ce71e3-2cf1-45e6-9f31-1fafe74f80b7","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"2dedb76d-53e7-4134-9a48-34b01687b98e","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Your bank account pays interest with an EAR of 5%. What is the APR quote for this account based on semiannual compounding? What is the APR with monthly compounding?","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]},{"object":"block","type":"list-item","data":{"direction":"auto"},"ref":"b7e76714-cab4-41fd-bdae-83f38ffea3bf","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"4e54e803-92dd-4968-a0d0-1431808c5c66","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Suppose the interest rate is 8% APR with monthly compounding. What is the present value of an annuity that pays $100 every six months for five years?","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]},{"object":"block","type":"list-item","data":{"direction":"auto"},"ref":"4a620abb-6c82-4fc6-ba31-2e6ff5931eb2","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"8676695e-8a37-4d56-981e-3da79ded8577","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"A payday loan is structured to obscure the true interest rate you are paying. For example, in Washington, you pay a $30 “fee” for a two-week $200 payday loan (when you repay the loan, you pay $230). What is the effective annual interest rate for this loan?","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]},{"object":"block","type":"list-item","data":{"direction":"auto"},"ref":"beedec76-48e8-4d3c-906c-2551b7f0f26a","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"83ee62f4-43e4-4499-a876-c1bd0a4517c7","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"You have been accepted into college. The college guarantees that your tuition will not increase for the four years you attend. The first $10,000 tuition payment is due in six months. After that, the same payment is due every six months until you have made a total of eight payments. The college offers a bank account that allows you to withdraw money every six months and has a fixed APR of 4% (semiannual) guaranteed to remain the same over the next four years. How much money must you deposit today if you intend to make no further deposits and would like to make all the tuition payments from this account, leaving the account empty when the last payment is made?","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}]}]}},"c